  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years imprisonment per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years for certain aggravated cases\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Potential forfeiture of assets related to the laundering activity\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Professional licensing restrictions\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like the amount of money laundered, frequency of offenses, and involvement in other criminal activities. Federal prosecutors typically use statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act to pursue charges.",
